text.tspan: * Compact binary data storage, extensible metadata
* Fast random and parallel access, efficient, scalable
* Widely used in High Performance Computing
* HDF5 libraries exists for many languages
such as Python, Matlab, R, Java, .NET
* (Proprietary) file formats should not be an obstacle
* A convention of the hierarchical layout used to store
* A convention on how to represent geometric data
types in a spatial reference system and generic data
* A recommendation for a core set of metadata fields,
* Foster the usage of OBO concepts [obofoundry.org]
The Connectome File Format (CFF) integrates several community accepted data formats using an XML-based container description.
These data formats vary in the way they separate data and metadata, and how they structure and represent binary data in files.
Customized reader and writer libraries have to be developed across platform and programming languages for each binary data format,
furthermore some of the formats are text-based, thus lack random access and store data inefficently.
Here, we propose to extract the common underlying data types for neuroscientific datasets produced across a wide variety of
spatio-temporal scales and conceptual granularities, in order to define a hierarchical data layout, and thereby integrating binary data
with metadata using Hierarchical Data Format (HDF5) as data container.
Neuroinformatics will have to provide generic solutions for storage and exchange of large amounts of complex neuroscience data.
In the bioinformatics community, BioHDF [www.biohdf.org] is developed along similar lines to handle the massive amounts of
data produced by next generation sequencing methods.
Stephan Gerhard, Signal Processing Laboratory 5 EPFL & Radiology CHUV, Lausanne
N-dimensional arrays with spatial, temporal and other dimensions
Examples: microscopy, MRI, gene expression, electrophysiology
Two classes of datasets: a) spatio-temporal datasets
mapped to a spatial reference system,
b) generic datasets with data schema as metadata
A unifying reference system for spatio-temporal datasets
An affine transformation defines the local coordinate system
of the Region. Regular and irregular datasets are components
of the Region and can define their own relative transformation.
Regions can be nested and define multi-scale data space
representations. Regions and datasets are mapped hierarchically
to NeuroHDF with appropriate metadata fields.
Metadata adds semantics and refers to ontologies
